All plans include the core platform: CRM, pipeline management, email marketing, SMS (usage-based), workflow automation, funnel builder, calendar/scheduling, reputation management, and reporting.

The differences are about scale, not features.

<h2 id="starter">Starter Plan -- $97/mo</h2>

<p><strong>What you get:</strong> One account (sub-account) with the full feature set. CRM, pipelines, automation, email, SMS, funnels, calendars, and reporting.</p>

<p><strong>What you don't get:</strong> No additional sub-accounts, no Snapshots, no white-labeling.</p>

<p><strong>Who it's for:</strong> Single-location businesses testing GHL before committing to the Agency tier. If you're running one location and want to see if GHL's automation and CRM work for your operation, Starter is the right entry point.</p>

<p><strong>My take:</strong> Starter is a good trial plan but not a long-term home for operators. The moment you add a second location or want to clone your setup, you need Agency Unlimited. I'd recommend using the 30-day free trial to evaluate GHL, then going directly to Agency Unlimited if it works for your operation.</p>

<h2 id="agency">Agency Unlimited Plan -- $297/mo</h2>

<p><strong>What you get:</strong> Everything in Starter plus unlimited sub-accounts, Snapshots (clone entire account configurations), white-label desktop app, and branded client portals.</p>

<p><strong>This is the operator tier.</strong> Here's why:</p>

<p><strong>Unlimited sub-accounts</strong> means every location gets its own isolated environment. Location A's contacts, pipelines, and automations are completely separate from Location B's. You manage everything from one agency dashboard but each location's data stays clean. At 5 locations or 50, the price doesn't change.</p>

<p><strong>Snapshots</strong> let you capture your entire proven setup and deploy it to new sub-accounts in about 3 minutes. Every pipeline, workflow, email template, funnel page, custom field, and tag -- cloned instantly. This feature alone justifies the $297/mo for any operator managing more than 2-3 locations.</p>

<p><strong>The math:</strong> At 10 locations, you're paying $29.70 per location per month. At 50 locations, you're paying $5.94 per location per month. Compare that to any CRM charging per-seat or per-location pricing and the economics are clear.</p>

<p><strong>My take:</strong> This is the plan I use. It runs my entire our operation across thousands of venues. The unlimited sub-accounts and Snapshots are non-negotiable for multi-location operators. If GHL is right for your business, this is the tier you should be on.</p>

<h2 id="saas">SaaS Pro Plan -- $497/mo</h2>

<p><strong>What you get:</strong> Everything in Agency Unlimited plus SaaS Mode (resell GHL as your own branded platform), rebilling (charge your clients for phone, email, and SMS usage through your brand), advanced API access, and priority support.</p>

<p><strong>Who it's for:</strong> Agencies and operators who want to white-label GHL as their own SaaS product and charge clients monthly for access. You become a software company, essentially reselling GHL under your own brand with your own pricing.</p>

<p><strong>My take:</strong> Unless you're building a software business on top of GHL, you don't need this. The rebilling feature is valuable if you have clients who need their own GHL access and you want to mark up the cost. But for operators using GHL to run their own multi-location business, Agency Unlimited has everything you need.</p>

<h2 id="hidden-costs">Hidden Costs to Know About</h2>

GHL's flat-rate pricing is straightforward, but there are usage-based costs that aren't included in the subscription:

<h3>SMS and Phone -- Usage-Based</h3>

SMS and phone calls are billed on usage through Twilio (integrated into GHL). Rates:
<ul>
  <li>SMS: ~$0.0079 per segment sent, ~$0.0079 per segment received</li>
  <li>Phone: ~$0.013/min outbound, ~$0.0085/min inbound</li>
  <li>Phone numbers: ~$1.15/mo per number</li>
</ul>

For most operators, SMS costs run $20-100/mo depending on volume. Phone costs are additional if you use GHL's built-in calling. These costs are per sub-account, so they scale with your location count and usage.

<h3>Email Sending</h3>

GHL includes email sending via Mailgun on all plans. Default sending (shared infrastructure) is included. For better deliverability, you'll want to set up a dedicated sending domain, which costs:
<ul>
  <li>Mailgun dedicated sending: included, but you need your own domain ($10-15/yr)</li>
  <li>Email warm-up period: 2-4 weeks of gradually increasing send volume</li>
</ul>

The email sending itself is included in the subscription -- there's no per-email charge. But the deliverability work (domain setup, warm-up, monitoring) requires your time.

<h3>Twilio/Mailgun Account Setup</h3>

GHL connects to Twilio for SMS/phone and Mailgun for email through LC (Lead Connector) Phone and Email. Setup requires creating accounts with these services and connecting them to GHL. This is a one-time setup but it adds complexity.

<h3>Premium Triggers and Actions</h3>

Some workflow triggers and actions are classified as "premium" and incur small per-use charges. Most operators won't hit these unless they're using advanced AI features or high-volume webhook triggers.

